    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2015-January/007189.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The email conversations from January 23, 2015, discuss various options for a hard fork in Bitcoin. One proposal is to use a soft-fork alternative that requires special outputs, but this approach is deemed unreasonable due to limitations on existing coins and required software updates for senders. Instead, a straightforward soft-fork approach using a new signature type for newly created addresses is suggested. Additionally, SIGHASH_WITHINPUTVALUE is proposed as a way to sign input values with TxOut scripts, which could simplify firmware and reduce security risks for devices like TREZOR. However, there is no soft-fork way to achieve this benefit without changing the way coins are originated, making it incompatible with existing coins.The discussion also covers the challenges of working with limited memory in the embedded world and the need for optimization to reduce complexity and improve security. Suggestions include using a table to avoid retransmitting reused transactions and streaming transactions along with their inputs interleaved to reduce memory requirements. Overall, the email conversations highlight the technical complexities and tradeoffs involved in implementing changes to the Bitcoin protocol.Another issue discussed in the emails is the risk of attackers isolating a node and tricking the user into signing away their entire wallet to fees, which can then be sold to a mining pool for mining before the user realizes what has happened. To reduce financial risk, it is suggested that nodes not relay excessive fee transactions, although this is not a complete solution. In the world of online-offline communication channels, a proposal has been put forth that aims to increase options for security. The proposal suggests upgrading signers, but it's an optional upgrade and not mandatory. This proposal is believed to simplify HW and create various online-offline communication channels. Alan, an expert in the field, highly encourages the proposal to be considered at some point.Finally, there is discussion around the vulnerability of an isolated node being attacked, where an attacker isolates a node and gets the owner to sign away their whole wallet to fee, which is then sold to a mining pool to mine before the owner can figure out what has happened. Tamas Blummer suggests that nodes should avoid relaying excessive fee transactions to reduce financial risk, although there are no further details regarding what specific risks these are or how they can be reduced.</summary>
